    <main class="main">
      <div class="content">
        <div class="hero fade-up" id="hero">
          <div class="day-pill">Day 02 &mdash; Phase 1 &mdash; Week 1</div>
          <h1 class="hero-title">
            Two Pointers<br />&amp; <em>Sliding Window</em>
          </h1>
          <p class="hero-lead">
            Yesterday you traded space for time with hash maps. Today you trade
            <em>neither</em>. Two Pointers and Sliding Window both run in O(n)
            with O(1) extra space &mdash; by being clever about which work you
            never need to do. These are the most elegant patterns in DSA.
            Internalize them and you'll recognize them in a third of all medium
            problems.
          </p>
          <div class="hero-tags">
            <span class="tag r">Two Pointers</span
            ><span class="tag t">Sliding Window</span
            ><span class="tag g">Fixed Window</span
            ><span class="tag p">Variable Window</span
            ><span class="tag gr">3Sum</span
            ><span class="tag r">4 Problems</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="callout info">
          <div class="callout-title">
            &#128260; Review First &mdash; 5 Minutes
          </div>
          <p>
            Before starting: implement <code>two_sum</code> (hash map) and
            <code>group_anagrams</code> from scratch, from memory. No looking.
            If you cannot, re-read Day 1 first. This morning ritual runs every
            day from here on.
          </p>
        </div>
        <hr class="divider" />
        <section class="section" id="two-pointers">
          <div class="section-number">
            Section 01 <span class="sn-label">Two Pointers</span>
          </div>
          <h2 class="sec-title">Two <em>Pointers</em></h2>
          <p class="sec-lead">
            Two Pointers maintains two index variables that move through the
            array in a coordinated way. The core insight: on a
            <strong>sorted array</strong>, the sum of any pair tells you exactly
            which pointer to advance &mdash; and advancing it permanently
            eliminates every pair involving that element. O(n²) becomes O(n)
            with zero extra space.
          </p>
          <div class="video-wrap">
            <div class="video-label">
              &#127902; <span>START HERE</span> &mdash; Two Pointers &mdash;
              NeetCode (8 min)
            </div>
            <iframe
              src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/VEPCm3BZEcw"
              allowfullscreen
              loading="lazy"
            ></iframe>
          </div>
          <div class="sub" id="tp-mental">
            <h3 class="sub-title">
              <span class="sub-num">1.1</span>The Mental Model: Eliminating
              Search Space
            </h3>
            <div class="mental-model">
              <h4>
                &#129504; Two Pointers = Permanently Eliminating Candidates
              </h4>
              <p>
                At every step ask:
                <strong>which of these two elements is forever useless?</strong>
                If <code>arr[L] + arr[R] &lt; target</code>, then
                <code>arr[L]</code> paired with <em>any</em> value &le;
                <code>arr[R]</code> is also too small &mdash; so L can never be
                in the answer. Advance L and permanently eliminate it.
                Symmetrically for R.
                <strong>n eliminations, one per step, O(n) total.</strong>
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="diagram">
              <div class="diag-title">
                The Invariant: Why Two Pointers Is Provably Correct
              </div>
              <pre class="diag-pre">
  Sorted: [-4, -1, -1,  0,  1,  2,  6,  9]    Target: 8
          L=0                             R=7

  Step 1: -4 + 9 = 5 &lt; 8
          For ALL r' &lt;= 7: nums[0]+nums[r'] &lt;= -4+9 = 5 &lt; 8
          So nums[0]=-4 CANNOT be in any valid pair. Advance L.

  Step 2: -1 + 9 = 8 = target. FOUND [indices 1, 7]

  If sum was 10 &gt; 8:
          For ALL l' &gt;= 1: nums[l']+nums[7] &gt;= -1+9 = 8 &gt;= 10? No.
          Actually: nums[l']+9 &gt;= -1+9 = 8 &gt; target means 9 paired
          with anything &gt;= nums[L] is also too big. Advance R.

  At most n total moves. Neither pointer ever reverses. QED.</pre
              >
            </div>
            <div class="callout insight">
              <div class="callout-title">
                &#128161; Why Sorting First Is Almost Always Worth It
              </div>
              <p>
                Sorting costs O(n log n) and enables O(n) two-pointer passes. If
                brute force is O(n&sup2;), then sort + two-pointer = O(n log n)
                + O(n) = O(n log n).
                <strong
                  >Without monotonicity (sorted order), you cannot safely
                  eliminate candidates. That is the fundamental
                  precondition.</strong
                >
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="sub" id="tp-twosum2">
            <h3 class="sub-title">
              <span class="sub-num">1.2</span>Two Sum II &mdash; The Full
              Thinking Process
            </h3>
            <p class="prose">
              LC #167. Sorted array, find two 1-indexed positions whose values
              sum to target. O(1) extra space required &mdash; hash map
              explicitly disallowed. We build from naive to optimal, with the
              precise reasoning at each step.
            </p>
            <div class="think-steps">
              <div class="think-step step-brute">
                <div class="think-step-header">
                  <div class="think-step-num">&#128308; Brute Force</div>
                  <div class="think-step-title">Try Every Pair</div>
                  <div class="think-step-complexity">
                    O(n&sup2;) time &middot; O(1) space
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="think-step-body">
                  Two nested loops. No use of sorted order &mdash; pure
                  exhaustion. For n=10,000:
                  <strong>~50 million pair checks</strong>.
                </p>
                <div class="code-block">
                  <div class="code-head">
                    <span class="code-lang">python</span
                    ><span class="code-label"
                      >brute force &mdash; try all pairs</span
                    ><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">
                      copy
                    </button>
                  </div>
                  <pre><code><span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">two_sum_sorted_brute</span>(nums, target):
    <span class="kw">for</span> i <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(<span class="py-bi">len</span>(nums)):
        <span class="kw">for</span> j <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(i + 1, <span class="py-bi">len</span>(nums)):
            <span class="kw">if</span> nums[i] + nums[j] == target:
                <span class="kw">return</span> [i + 1, j + 1]  <span class="cm"># 1-indexed</span>
    <span class="kw">return</span> []

<span class="cm"># Time:  O(n²) — nested loops, no use of sorted order
# Space: O(1) — no extra data structures
# For n=10,000: ~50 million pair checks</span></code></pre>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="think-arrow">
                &#9660; &nbsp;sorted array &mdash; can we exploit sorted order
                beyond breaking early?
              </div>
              <div class="think-step step-better">
                <div class="think-step-header">
                  <div class="think-step-num">&#128992; Insight</div>
                  <div class="think-step-title">
                    Exploit Sorted Order: Early Termination
                  </div>
                  <div class="think-step-complexity">
                    O(n&sup2;) worst &middot; O(1) space
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="think-step-body">
                  Sorted means if <code>nums[i]+nums[j] &gt; target</code>, all
                  larger j are also too big &mdash; break. Improves average
                  case. But O(n&sup2;) worst case remains. Reveals the key:
                  <strong
                    >sorted order tells us when a direction is futile.</strong
                  >
                </p>
                <div class="code-block">
                  <div class="code-head">
                    <span class="code-lang">python</span
                    ><span class="code-label"
                      >early termination &mdash; not yet optimal</span
                    ><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">
                      copy
                    </button>
                  </div>
                  <pre><code><span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">two_sum_sorted_better</span>(nums, target):
    <span class="kw">for</span> i <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(<span class="py-bi">len</span>(nums)):
        <span class="kw">for</span> j <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(i + 1, <span class="py-bi">len</span>(nums)):
            total = nums[i] + nums[j]
            <span class="kw">if</span> total == target:
                <span class="kw">return</span> [i + 1, j + 1]
            <span class="kw">if</span> total &gt; target:
                <span class="kw">break</span>  <span class="cm"># sorted: no larger j can help — break inner loop</span>
    <span class="kw">return</span> []

<span class="cm"># Still O(n²) worst case, but improved average case.
# The insight: sorted order tells us WHEN a direction is futile.
# But we still restart the inner loop from scratch each time.
# Can we eliminate the inner loop entirely?</span></code></pre>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="think-arrow">
                &#9660; &nbsp;we still have an inner O(n) loop &mdash; can we
                eliminate it entirely with one pass?
              </div>
              <div class="think-step step-optimal">
                <div class="think-step-header">
                  <div class="think-step-num">&#128994; Optimal</div>
                  <div class="think-step-title">
                    Two Pointers &mdash; One Pass, Zero Extra Space
                  </div>
                  <div class="think-step-complexity">
                    O(n) time &middot; O(1) space
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="think-step-body">
                  <strong>Full insight:</strong> instead of fixing i and
                  scanning j, place pointers at both extremes. Each step, one
                  extreme is permanently eliminated. No inner loop.
                </p>
                <div class="code-block">
                  <div class="code-head">
                    <span class="code-lang">python</span
                    ><span class="code-label"
                      >two pointers &mdash; O(n) with invariant proof</span
                    ><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">
                      copy
                    </button>
                  </div>
                  <pre><code><span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">two_sum_sorted</span>(nums, target):
    left, right = 0, <span class="py-bi">len</span>(nums) - 1

    <span class="kw">while</span> left &lt; right:
        total = nums[left] + nums[right]

        <span class="kw">if</span> total == target:
            <span class="kw">return</span> [left + 1, right + 1]    <span class="cm"># 1-indexed (LC 167)</span>
        <span class="kw">elif</span> total &lt; target:
            left += 1    <span class="cm"># nums[left] too small for ANY right &lt;= current</span>
        <span class="kw">else</span>:
            right -= 1   <span class="cm"># nums[right] too big for ANY left &gt;= current</span>

    <span class="kw">return</span> []

<span class="cm"># Time:  O(n)  — each pointer moves at most n times total
# Space: O(1)  — two integer variables

# THE INVARIANT PROOF:
# When total &lt; target:
#   For all r' &lt;= right: nums[left]+nums[r'] &lt;= nums[left]+nums[right] &lt; target
#   So nums[left] CANNOT be part of any valid pair. Advance left. QED.
# When total &gt; target: symmetric argument for right.
# Therefore: no valid pair is ever skipped.</span></code></pre>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="complexity-row">
              <div class="cb cb-bad">
                <span class="cb-label">Brute Force</span>O(n&sup2;)
              </div>
              <div class="cb cb-time">
                <span class="cb-label">Two Pointers</span>O(n)
              </div>
              <div class="cb cb-space">
                <span class="cb-label">Space</span>O(1)
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="callout tip">
              <div class="callout-title">
                &#9989; Interview Move: State the Invariant
              </div>
              <p>
                After writing the optimal solution, add a comment:
                <em
                  >"left is eliminated when sum &lt; target because nums[left]
                  paired with any value &le; nums[right] is also too small."</em
                >
                This demonstrates you understand <em>why</em> the algorithm
                works, not just <em>how</em>.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="sub" id="tp-palindrome">
            <h3 class="sub-title">
              <span class="sub-num">1.3</span>Palindromes &mdash; Convergence as
              Symmetry Checking
            </h3>
            <p class="prose">
              The second major two-pointer pattern: verify a palindrome.
              Pointers converge inward, checking corresponding positions
              simultaneously. Generalizes to any problem requiring comparison
              from both ends.
            </p>
            <div class="think-steps">
              <div class="think-step step-brute">
                <div class="think-step-header">
                  <div class="think-step-num">&#128308; Brute Force</div>
                  <div class="think-step-title">Reverse and Compare</div>
                  <div class="think-step-complexity">
                    O(n) time &middot; O(n) space
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="think-step-body">
                  Create a reversed copy and compare. Correct but O(n) extra
                  memory for the copy &mdash; entirely unnecessary.
                </p>
                <div class="code-block">
                  <div class="code-head">
                    <span class="code-lang">python</span
                    ><span class="code-label"
                      >reverse and compare &mdash; O(n) space wasted</span
                    ><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">
                      copy
                    </button>
                  </div>
                  <pre><code><span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">is_palindrome_brute</span>(s):
    <span class="kw">return</span> s == s[::-1]

<span class="cm"># s[::-1] creates a new string of length n — O(n) extra memory.
# Then comparison is O(n). Total: O(n) time, O(n) space.
# The copy is created, compared, then thrown away.
# We can do the same comparison in-place with O(1) space.</span></code></pre>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="think-step step-better">
                <div class="think-step-header">
                  <div class="think-step-num">&#128994; Optimal</div>
                  <div class="think-step-title">
                    In-Place Two Pointers &mdash; O(1) Space
                  </div>
                  <div class="think-step-complexity">
                    O(n) time &middot; O(1) space
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="think-step-body">
                  Pointers at both ends, move inward. One mismatch &rarr; not a
                  palindrome. Meet in the middle &rarr; palindrome. Zero
                  allocation. Extension: LC #680 allows deleting one character.
                </p>
                <div class="code-block">
                  <div class="code-head">
                    <span class="code-lang">python</span
                    ><span class="code-label"
                      >in-place palindrome check + Valid Palindrome II
                      extension</span
                    ><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">
                      copy
                    </button>
                  </div>
                  <pre><code><span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">is_palindrome</span>(s):
    left, right = 0, <span class="py-bi">len</span>(s) - 1
    <span class="kw">while</span> left &lt; right:
        <span class="kw">if</span> s[left] != s[right]:
            <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="kw">False</span>
        left += 1
        right -= 1
    <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="kw">True</span>
<span class="cm"># O(n) time, O(1) space — never allocates anything</span>


<span class="cm"># LC #680: Valid Palindrome II — can delete AT MOST one character</span>
<span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">valid_palindrome_ii</span>(s):
    <span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">is_pal</span>(l, r):
        <span class="kw">while</span> l &lt; r:
            <span class="kw">if</span> s[l] != s[r]: <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="kw">False</span>
            l += 1; r -= 1
        <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="kw">True</span>

    left, right = 0, <span class="py-bi">len</span>(s) - 1
    <span class="kw">while</span> left &lt; right:
        <span class="kw">if</span> s[left] == s[right]:
            left += 1; right -= 1
        <span class="kw">else</span>:
            <span class="cm"># ONE deletion allowed: try skipping left OR skipping right</span>
            <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">is_pal</span>(left + 1, right) <span class="kw">or</span> <span class="fn">is_pal</span>(left, right - 1)
    <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="kw">True</span>

<span class="cm"># Time: O(n) — at most two full passes
# Space: O(1)
# The "two choices on mismatch" pattern recurs in harder problems.</span></code></pre>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="sub" id="tp-3sum">
            <h3 class="sub-title">
              <span class="sub-num t">1.4</span>3Sum &mdash; Reducing N-Sum to
              Two Pointers
            </h3>
            <p class="prose">
              LC #15. Find all unique triplets summing to zero. Pattern:
              <strong>sort, fix one element, two-pointer the rest.</strong> The
              logic is straightforward. The duplicate handling is where everyone
              fails.
            </p>
            <div class="callout warn">
              <div class="callout-title">
                &#9888;&#65039; The Duplicate Trap &mdash; Two Places, Both
                Required
              </div>
              <p>
                You must skip duplicates at <strong>exactly two places</strong>.
                <strong>Skip #1:</strong> outer loop &mdash; if current element
                equals previous, skip (prevents re-fixing the same outer value).
                <strong>Skip #2:</strong> after finding a valid triplet inside
                the two-pointer loop &mdash; advance L and R past all their
                duplicate values. Missing skip #1: duplicate outer elements
                produce duplicate triplets. Missing skip #2: duplicate inner
                pairs produce duplicate triplets.
                <strong>Both must be present.</strong>
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="think-steps">
              <div class="think-step step-brute">
                <div class="think-step-header">
                  <div class="think-step-num">&#128308; Brute Force</div>
                  <div class="think-step-title">Three Nested Loops</div>
                  <div class="think-step-complexity">
                    O(n&sup3;) time &middot; O(1) space
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="think-step-body">
                  Try every triplet (i,j,k). For n=3000:
                  <strong>4.5 billion iterations</strong>. Completely unusable.
                </p>
                <div class="code-block">
                  <div class="code-head">
                    <span class="code-lang">python</span
                    ><span class="code-label">O(n&sup3;) brute force</span
                    ><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">
                      copy
                    </button>
                  </div>
                  <pre><code><span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">three_sum_brute</span>(nums):
    result = <span class="py-bi">set</span>()
    n = <span class="py-bi">len</span>(nums)
    <span class="kw">for</span> i <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(n):
        <span class="kw">for</span> j <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(i + 1, n):
            <span class="kw">for</span> k <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(j + 1, n):
                <span class="kw">if</span> nums[i] + nums[j] + nums[k] == 0:
                    result.add(<span class="py-bi">tuple</span>(<span class="py-bi">sorted</span>([nums[i], nums[j], nums[k]])))
    <span class="kw">return</span> [<span class="py-bi">list</span>(t) <span class="kw">for</span> t <span class="kw">in</span> result]

<span class="cm"># O(n³) — for n=3000: 4.5 billion iterations. Times out instantly.</span></code></pre>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="think-arrow">
                &#9660; &nbsp;fix one element &mdash; reduces to a two-sum
                problem
              </div>
              <div class="think-step step-better">
                <div class="think-step-header">
                  <div class="think-step-num">&#128992; Better</div>
                  <div class="think-step-title">Fix One + Hash Set</div>
                  <div class="think-step-complexity">
                    O(n&sup2;) time &middot; O(n) space
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="think-step-body">
                  Fix i, find pair summing to <code>-nums[i]</code> with a hash
                  set. O(n&sup2;) but O(n) extra space per outer iteration.
                  Duplicate handling via set is implicit &mdash; opaque in
                  interviews.
                </p>
                <div class="code-block">
                  <div class="code-head">
                    <span class="code-lang">python</span
                    ><span class="code-label">O(n&sup2;) hash approach</span
                    ><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">
                      copy
                    </button>
                  </div>
                  <pre><code><span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">three_sum_hash</span>(nums):
    nums.sort()
    result = <span class="py-bi">set</span>()
    <span class="kw">for</span> i, a <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">enumerate</span>(nums):
        seen = <span class="py-bi">set</span>()  <span class="cm"># O(n) extra space per outer iteration</span>
        <span class="kw">for</span> j <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(i + 1, <span class="py-bi">len</span>(nums)):
            complement = -a - nums[j]
            <span class="kw">if</span> complement <span class="kw">in</span> seen:
                result.add(<span class="py-bi">tuple</span>(<span class="py-bi">sorted</span>([a, complement, nums[j]])))
            seen.add(nums[j])
    <span class="kw">return</span> [<span class="py-bi">list</span>(t) <span class="kw">for</span> t <span class="kw">in</span> result]

<span class="cm"># O(n²) time but O(n) extra space.
# Duplicate handling via a set is implicit — harder to reason about in interviews.
# The two-pointer approach handles duplicates explicitly and uses O(1) space.</span></code></pre>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="think-arrow">
                &#9660; &nbsp;fix one element + sorted remainder &mdash; use two
                pointers instead of hash set
              </div>
              <div class="think-step step-optimal">
                <div class="think-step-header">
                  <div class="think-step-num">&#128994; Optimal</div>
                  <div class="think-step-title">Sort + Fix + Two Pointers</div>
                  <div class="think-step-complexity">
                    O(n&sup2;) time &middot; O(1) extra space
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="think-step-body">
                  Sort once. Fix i with explicit skip. Two pointers on sorted
                  remainder. Explicit duplicate skips after each found triplet.
                  Same O(n&sup2;) as hash, O(1) extra space, transparent logic.
                </p>
                <div class="code-block">
                  <div class="code-head">
                    <span class="code-lang">python</span
                    ><span class="code-label"
                      >3sum &mdash; canonical solution with annotated duplicate
                      skips</span
                    ><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">
                      copy
                    </button>
                  </div>
                  <pre><code><span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">three_sum</span>(nums):
    nums.sort()   <span class="cm"># O(n log n) — enables two pointers + explicit dup handling</span>
    result = []

    <span class="kw">for</span> i, a <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">enumerate</span>(nums):

        <span class="cm"># DUPLICATE SKIP #1: same value as previous outer element</span>
        <span class="cm"># All triplets we'd find are already in result.</span>
        <span class="kw">if</span> i &gt; 0 <span class="kw">and</span> nums[i] == nums[i - 1]:
            <span class="kw">continue</span>

        <span class="cm"># EARLY EXIT: sorted array — if smallest element &gt; 0,</span>
        <span class="cm"># no triplet can ever sum to 0.</span>
        <span class="kw">if</span> a &gt; 0:
            <span class="kw">break</span>

        left, right = i + 1, <span class="py-bi">len</span>(nums) - 1

        <span class="kw">while</span> left &lt; right:
            total = a + nums[left] + nums[right]

            <span class="kw">if</span> total == 0:
                result.append([a, nums[left], nums[right]])

                <span class="cm"># DUPLICATE SKIP #2: skip duplicate L and R values</span>
                <span class="kw">while</span> left &lt; right <span class="kw">and</span> nums[left] == nums[left + 1]:
                    left += 1
                <span class="kw">while</span> left &lt; right <span class="kw">and</span> nums[right] == nums[right - 1]:
                    right -= 1
                left += 1
                right -= 1

            <span class="kw">elif</span> total &lt; 0:
                left += 1
            <span class="kw">else</span>:
                right -= 1

    <span class="kw">return</span> result

<span class="cm"># Time:  O(n log n) + O(n²) = O(n²)
# Space: O(1) extra — result list doesn't count
# The inner "while skip" loops are O(n) TOTAL across all outer iterations,
# not O(n) per iteration. They share the same pointer movement budget.</span></code></pre>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="complexity-row">
              <div class="cb cb-bad">
                <span class="cb-label">3 Loops</span>O(n&sup3;)
              </div>
              <div class="cb cb-ok">
                <span class="cb-label">Hash</span>O(n&sup2;)
              </div>
              <div class="cb cb-time">
                <span class="cb-label">Two Pointers</span>O(n&sup2;)
              </div>
              <div class="cb cb-space">
                <span class="cb-label">Extra Space</span>O(1)
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="callout tip">
              <div class="callout-title">
                &#9989; The N-Sum Pattern Generalizes
              </div>
              <p>
                4Sum = two outer loops (skip dups at each level) + two pointers
                on innermost. kSum = fix (k-2) elements with nested loops,
                two-pointer the last two. Time: O(n<sup>k-1</sup>). Always sort
                first.
                <strong>kSum reduces to (k-1)Sum by fixing one element.</strong>
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>
        <hr class="divider" />
        <section class="section" id="sliding-window">
          <div class="section-number">
            Section 02 <span class="sn-label">Sliding Window</span>
          </div>
          <h2 class="sec-title">Sliding <em>Window</em></h2>
          <p class="sec-lead">
            Sliding Window finds subarrays or substrings satisfying a condition
            in O(n) by incrementally maintaining a window as it moves across the
            array. The window state is updated in O(1) per step: add one element
            on the right, remove one on the left. Two types: fixed-size and
            variable-size.
          </p>
          <div class="video-wrap">
            <div class="video-label">
              &#127902; <span>ESSENTIAL</span> &mdash; Sliding Window &mdash;
              NeetCode (14 min)
            </div>
            <iframe
              src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/MK-NZ4hF9Gg"
              allowfullscreen
              loading="lazy"
            ></iframe>
          </div>
          <div class="sub" id="sw-types">
            <h3 class="sub-title">
              <span class="sub-num">2.1</span>Fixed vs Variable &mdash; Two
              Mental Models
            </h3>
            <div class="mental-model">
              <h4>&#129504; Two Flavors of Sliding Window</h4>
              <p>
                <strong>Fixed window (size k given):</strong> build the first
                window in O(k), then slide &mdash; each step add right element,
                remove left element. Formula:
                <code>sum = sum + arr[right] - arr[right-k]</code>. O(1) per
                step, O(n) total. <br /><br /><strong
                  >Variable window (size unknown):</strong
                >
                expand right freely, shrink left when the window violates a
                condition. The tricky part: knowing exactly <em>when</em> to
                shrink and what to track.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="diagram">
              <div class="diag-title">
                Fixed Window &mdash; Sliding a Window of Size k
              </div>
              <pre class="diag-pre">
  nums = [2, 1, 5, 1, 3, 2],  k = 3    Goal: max sum

  Build:        [2, 1, 5]  sum = 8
  Slide right:  add 1, remove 2  [1, 5, 1]  sum = 8-2+1 = 7
  Slide right:  add 3, remove 1  [5, 1, 3]  sum = 7-1+3 = 9  &lt;- max
  Slide right:  add 2, remove 5  [1, 3, 2]  sum = 9-5+2 = 6

  Every slide is O(1). Total: O(n). NOT O(n*k).
  The formula: sum = sum + nums[i] - nums[i-k]</pre
              >
            </div>
            <div class="diagram">
              <div class="diag-title">
                Variable Window &mdash; Longest Substring Without Repeat
              </div>
              <pre class="diag-pre">
  s = "a  b  c  a  b  c  b  b"
          L              R     window tracks {chars in L..R}

  R=0: {a}        "a"    len=1  (expand: no duplicate)
  R=1: {a,b}      "ab"   len=2  (expand: no duplicate)
  R=2: {a,b,c}    "abc"  len=3  (expand: no duplicate)
  R=3: "a" in set! SHRINK: remove s[L=0]="a", L-&gt;1. {b,c,a} len=3
  R=4: "b" in set! SHRINK: remove s[L=1]="b", L-&gt;2. {c,a,b} len=3
  R=5: "c" in set! SHRINK: remove s[L=2]="c", L-&gt;3. {a,b,c} len=3
  R=6: "b" in set! SHRINK: L-&gt;4 (removes "a"), L-&gt;5 (removes "b"). len=2
  R=7: "b" in set! SHRINK: L-&gt;6 (removes "c"). len=1

  Answer: 3. Total pointer moves: right=8, left=7. 2n = O(n).</pre
              >
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="sub" id="sw-fixed">
            <h3 class="sub-title">
              <span class="sub-num t">2.2</span>Fixed Window &mdash; Max Sum
              Subarray of Size k
            </h3>
            <p class="prose">
              The simplest sliding window. Establishes the core formula. Every
              fixed-window problem is a variation.
            </p>
            <div class="think-steps">
              <div class="think-step step-brute">
                <div class="think-step-header">
                  <div class="think-step-num">&#128308; Brute Force</div>
                  <div class="think-step-title">
                    Recompute Every Window from Scratch
                  </div>
                  <div class="think-step-complexity">
                    O(n&middot;k) time &middot; O(1) space
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="think-step-body">
                  For each start, sum the next k elements. Adjacent windows
                  share k-1 elements &mdash; all repeated work. For n=10,000 and
                  k=1,000: ten million additions.
                </p>
                <div class="code-block">
                  <div class="code-head">
                    <span class="code-lang">python</span
                    ><span class="code-label"
                      >O(n*k) &mdash; recomputing every window</span
                    ><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">
                      copy
                    </button>
                  </div>
                  <pre><code><span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">max_sum_brute</span>(nums, k):
    <span class="kw">if</span> <span class="py-bi">len</span>(nums) &lt; k: <span class="kw">return</span> -1
    max_sum = <span class="py-bi">float</span>(<span class="st">&#39;-inf&#39;</span>)
    <span class="kw">for</span> i <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(<span class="py-bi">len</span>(nums) - k + 1):
        window_sum = <span class="py-bi">sum</span>(nums[i : i + k])  <span class="cm"># O(k) work per window</span>
        max_sum = <span class="py-bi">max</span>(max_sum, window_sum)
    <span class="kw">return</span> max_sum

<span class="cm"># O(n * k): for n=10,000 and k=1,000 → 10 million additions.
# Adjacent windows [i..i+k] and [i+1..i+k+1] share k-1 elements.
# We recompute those k-1 elements every single iteration.
# Can we update the sum in O(1) instead of O(k)?</span></code></pre>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="think-step step-better">
                <div class="think-step-header">
                  <div class="think-step-num">&#128994; Optimal</div>
                  <div class="think-step-title">
                    Slide: Add New Right, Remove Old Left
                  </div>
                  <div class="think-step-complexity">
                    O(n) time &middot; O(1) space
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="think-step-body">
                  Build first window in O(k). Each slide: one addition + one
                  subtraction = O(1). The core formula underlies every
                  fixed-window problem.
                </p>
                <div class="code-block">
                  <div class="code-head">
                    <span class="code-lang">python</span
                    ><span class="code-label"
                      >O(n) sliding window &mdash; the formula</span
                    ><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">
                      copy
                    </button>
                  </div>
                  <pre><code><span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">max_sum_sliding</span>(nums, k):
    <span class="kw">if</span> <span class="py-bi">len</span>(nums) &lt; k: <span class="kw">return</span> -1

    <span class="cm"># Build the first window: O(k)</span>
    window_sum = <span class="py-bi">sum</span>(nums[:k])
    max_sum = window_sum

    <span class="cm"># Slide: add incoming right element, subtract outgoing left element</span>
    <span class="kw">for</span> i <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(k, <span class="py-bi">len</span>(nums)):
        window_sum += nums[i] - nums[i - k]  <span class="cm"># THE FORMULA: O(1) per slide</span>
        max_sum = <span class="py-bi">max</span>(max_sum, window_sum)

    <span class="kw">return</span> max_sum

<span class="cm"># Time:  O(k) first window + O(n-k) slides = O(n)
# Space: O(1) — just two integers
#
# nums[i]     = element entering window on the right
# nums[i - k] = element leaving window on the left
# This formula is the foundation of ALL fixed-window problems.</span></code></pre>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="complexity-row">
              <div class="cb cb-bad">
                <span class="cb-label">Brute Force</span>O(n&middot;k)
              </div>
              <div class="cb cb-time">
                <span class="cb-label">Sliding Window</span>O(n)
              </div>
              <div class="cb cb-space">
                <span class="cb-label">Space</span>O(1)
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="sub" id="sw-variable">
            <h3 class="sub-title">
              <span class="sub-num p">2.3</span>Variable Window &mdash; Longest
              Substring Without Repeating Characters
            </h3>
            <p class="prose">
              LC #3. The canonical variable window problem. Window is valid when
              it contains no duplicate characters. When a duplicate enters,
              shrink from the left until it is gone.
              <strong
                >The crucial insight that makes it O(n): shrink, do not
                restart.</strong
              >
            </p>
            <div class="think-steps">
              <div class="think-step step-brute">
                <div class="think-step-header">
                  <div class="think-step-num">&#128308; Brute Force</div>
                  <div class="think-step-title">Check Every Substring</div>
                  <div class="think-step-complexity">
                    O(n&sup3;) time &middot; O(k) space
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="think-step-body">
                  O(n&sup2;) substring pairs &times; O(n) uniqueness check each
                  = O(n&sup3;). For n=1000: 1 billion operations.
                </p>
                <div class="code-block">
                  <div class="code-head">
                    <span class="code-lang">python</span
                    ><span class="code-label"
                      >O(n&sup3;) &mdash; every substring</span
                    ><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">
                      copy
                    </button>
                  </div>
                  <pre><code><span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">length_of_longest_brute</span>(s):
    n = <span class="py-bi">len</span>(s); max_len = 0
    <span class="kw">for</span> i <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(n):                      <span class="cm"># O(n) starting positions</span>
        <span class="kw">for</span> j <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(i, n):                  <span class="cm"># O(n) ending positions</span>
            sub = s[i:j+1]
            <span class="kw">if</span> <span class="py-bi">len</span>(<span class="py-bi">set</span>(sub)) == <span class="py-bi">len</span>(sub):  <span class="cm"># O(n) uniqueness check</span>
                max_len = <span class="py-bi">max</span>(max_len, j - i + 1)
    <span class="kw">return</span> max_len

<span class="cm"># O(n) × O(n) × O(n) = O(n³). For n=1000: 1 billion operations.</span></code></pre>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="think-arrow">
                &#9660; &nbsp;O(n&sup3;) &rarr; check uniqueness in O(1) per
                step with a set
              </div>
              <div class="think-step step-better">
                <div class="think-step-header">
                  <div class="think-step-num">&#128992; Better</div>
                  <div class="think-step-title">
                    Fix Start, Expand Until Duplicate, Restart
                  </div>
                  <div class="think-step-complexity">
                    O(n&sup2;) time &middot; O(k) space
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="think-step-body">
                  O(1) duplicate check per step now. But when duplicate found,
                  we throw away the entire set and recheck characters we just
                  validated. The wasted work is the problem.
                </p>
                <div class="code-block">
                  <div class="code-head">
                    <span class="code-lang">python</span
                    ><span class="code-label"
                      >O(n&sup2;) &mdash; restart throws away validated
                      work</span
                    ><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">
                      copy
                    </button>
                  </div>
                  <pre><code><span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">length_of_longest_better</span>(s):
    max_len = 0
    <span class="kw">for</span> i <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(<span class="py-bi">len</span>(s)):
        seen = <span class="py-bi">set</span>()                       <span class="cm"># reset window every outer iteration</span>
        <span class="kw">for</span> j <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(i, <span class="py-bi">len</span>(s)):
            <span class="kw">if</span> s[j] <span class="kw">in</span> seen:
                <span class="kw">break</span>                      <span class="cm"># duplicate found — abandon this window</span>
            seen.add(s[j])
            max_len = <span class="py-bi">max</span>(max_len, j - i + 1)
    <span class="kw">return</span> max_len

<span class="cm"># O(n²) — improved from O(n³) but still sub-optimal.
# The flaw: when we abandon and restart from i+1, we throw away the set
# and re-examine s[i+2], s[i+3], ... which we JUST validated.
# Key insight: those characters were already valid — we should KEEP them
# and only remove the one offending character from the left.</span></code></pre>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="think-arrow">
                &#9660; &nbsp;O(n&sup2;) &rarr; instead of restarting the
                window, shrink it from the left
              </div>
              <div class="think-step step-optimal">
                <div class="think-step-header">
                  <div class="think-step-num">&#128994; Optimal</div>
                  <div class="think-step-title">
                    Shrink Left Instead of Restarting
                  </div>
                  <div class="think-step-complexity">
                    O(n) time &middot; O(k) space
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="think-step-body">
                  <strong>The insight:</strong> instead of restarting, shrink
                  from the left until the duplicate is gone. The valid
                  characters to the right of the removed element are preserved.
                  Every character enters and leaves the window at most once.
                </p>
                <div class="code-block">
                  <div class="code-head">
                    <span class="code-lang">python</span
                    ><span class="code-label"
                      >O(n) sliding window &mdash; shrink don't restart + dict
                      variant</span
                    ><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">
                      copy
                    </button>
                  </div>
                  <pre><code><span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">length_of_longest</span>(s):
    char_set = <span class="py-bi">set</span>()  <span class="cm"># characters currently in the window</span>
    left = 0; max_len = 0

    <span class="kw">for</span> right <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(<span class="py-bi">len</span>(s)):
        <span class="cm"># Window violated: duplicate entered — shrink from left</span>
        <span class="kw">while</span> s[right] <span class="kw">in</span> char_set:
            char_set.remove(s[left])
            left += 1
        <span class="cm"># Now s[right] is NOT a duplicate — expand</span>
        char_set.add(s[right])
        max_len = <span class="py-bi">max</span>(max_len, right - left + 1)

    <span class="kw">return</span> max_len

<span class="cm"># Time:  O(n) — see amortized argument in callout below
# Space: O(k) — k = max window size (at most min(n, alphabet_size))


# Faster variant: dict stores last-seen index, left jumps directly</span>
<span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">length_of_longest_v2</span>(s):
    last_seen = {}  <span class="cm"># char → most recent index</span>
    left = 0; max_len = 0
    <span class="kw">for</span> right, c <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">enumerate</span>(s):
        <span class="kw">if</span> c <span class="kw">in</span> last_seen <span class="kw">and</span> last_seen[c] &gt;= left:
            left = last_seen[c] + 1  <span class="cm"># jump directly past the duplicate</span>
        last_seen[c] = right
        max_len = <span class="py-bi">max</span>(max_len, right - left + 1)
    <span class="kw">return</span> max_len

<span class="cm"># v2: left jumps over multiple chars at once instead of one-by-one.
# Same O(n) asymptotics but fewer iterations in practice.</span></code></pre>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="callout insight">
              <div class="callout-title">
                &#128161; The Amortized O(n) Argument &mdash; Must Know for
                Interviews
              </div>
              <p>
                The inner <code>while</code> loop looks like it could run O(n)
                per outer iteration, making it O(n&sup2;).
                <strong>It does not.</strong> The key: <code>left</code> only
                ever moves right &mdash; it never reverses. Across the
                <em>entire algorithm</em>, <code>left</code> advances at most n
                times total, regardless of how many individual while iterations
                fire per outer iteration. Total inner-loop cost across all
                iterations: O(n). Add O(n) outer: total O(n).
                <strong
                  >This argument applies to every single shrinking-window
                  problem.</strong
                >
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="sub" id="sw-min">
            <h3 class="sub-title">
              <span class="sub-num g">2.4</span>Minimum Window &mdash; Shrinking
              When Valid
            </h3>
            <p class="prose">
              LC #209. Minimum Size Subarray Sum. Find the shortest subarray
              with sum &ge; target. Critical variation:
              <strong>the shrink condition is inverted.</strong> You shrink
              <em>when the window is valid</em> to minimize length, not when it
              is violated. Getting this flip right separates average from strong
              candidates.
            </p>
            <div class="callout warn">
              <div class="callout-title">
                &#9888;&#65039; The Shrink Condition Flip
              </div>
              <p>
                For <em>maximum</em> windows: expand until violated, shrink
                until valid, record. For <em>minimum</em> windows: expand until
                valid, <strong>record, then shrink while still valid</strong>.
                The outer structure is identical. Only the shrink condition and
                record placement differ.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="think-steps">
              <div class="think-step step-brute">
                <div class="think-step-header">
                  <div class="think-step-num">&#128308; Brute Force</div>
                  <div class="think-step-title">Check Every Subarray</div>
                  <div class="think-step-complexity">
                    O(n&sup2;) time &middot; O(1) space
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="think-step-body">
                  For every start index, expand right until sum &ge; target.
                  O(n&sup2;) total.
                </p>
                <div class="code-block">
                  <div class="code-head">
                    <span class="code-lang">python</span
                    ><span class="code-label">O(n&sup2;) brute force</span
                    ><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">
                      copy
                    </button>
                  </div>
                  <pre><code><span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">min_subarray_sum_brute</span>(target, nums):
    n = <span class="py-bi">len</span>(nums)
    min_len = <span class="py-bi">float</span>(<span class="st">&#39;inf&#39;</span>)
    <span class="kw">for</span> i <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(n):
        curr_sum = 0
        <span class="kw">for</span> j <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(i, n):
            curr_sum += nums[j]
            <span class="kw">if</span> curr_sum &gt;= target:
                min_len = <span class="py-bi">min</span>(min_len, j - i + 1)
                <span class="kw">break</span>  <span class="cm"># can't get shorter starting from i</span>
    <span class="kw">return</span> min_len <span class="kw">if</span> min_len != <span class="py-bi">float</span>(<span class="st">&#39;inf&#39;</span>) <span class="kw">else</span> 0

<span class="cm"># O(n²) — for each start, scan right until sum &gt;= target</span></code></pre>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="think-step step-better">
                <div class="think-step-header">
                  <div class="think-step-num">&#128994; Optimal</div>
                  <div class="think-step-title">
                    Shrink While Valid &mdash; Inverted Condition
                  </div>
                  <div class="think-step-complexity">
                    O(n) time &middot; O(1) space
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="think-step-body">
                  Expand right always. When sum &ge; target: record length,
                  shrink from left, repeat. Keep shrinking as long as window
                  remains valid &mdash; each shrink might reveal a shorter valid
                  window.
                </p>
                <div class="code-block">
                  <div class="code-head">
                    <span class="code-lang">python</span
                    ><span class="code-label"
                      >O(n) minimum window &mdash; shrink when valid</span
                    ><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">
                      copy
                    </button>
                  </div>
                  <pre><code><span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">min_subarray_sum</span>(target, nums):
    left = 0; curr_sum = 0
    min_len = <span class="py-bi">float</span>(<span class="st">&#39;inf&#39;</span>)

    <span class="kw">for</span> right <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(<span class="py-bi">len</span>(nums)):
        curr_sum += nums[right]           <span class="cm"># EXPAND: always add right element</span>

        <span class="cm"># SHRINK: while window is VALID (sum &gt;= target), try to minimize</span>
        <span class="kw">while</span> curr_sum &gt;= target:
            min_len = <span class="py-bi">min</span>(min_len, right - left + 1)  <span class="cm"># record BEFORE shrinking</span>
            curr_sum -= nums[left]
            left += 1

    <span class="kw">return</span> min_len <span class="kw">if</span> min_len != <span class="py-bi">float</span>(<span class="st">&#39;inf&#39;</span>) <span class="kw">else</span> 0

<span class="cm"># Time:  O(n) — same amortized argument: left moves at most n times total
# Space: O(1)
#
# CONTRAST with longest-window problems:
#   Longest:  SHRINK while INVALID  → record AFTER shrink loop
#   Minimum:  SHRINK while VALID    → record INSIDE shrink loop (before removing left)
#
# The inversion: for minimum, we record every valid window size
# as we shrink it — we want the shortest, so we keep shrinking
# as long as the window remains valid.</span></code></pre>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="sub" id="sw-template">
            <h3 class="sub-title">
              <span class="sub-num gr">2.5</span>The Universal Variable Window
              Template
            </h3>
            <p class="prose">
              Every variable window problem is an instance of this skeleton. The
              only things that change: window state, validity condition, max vs
              min. Memorize the three steps.
            </p>
            <div class="code-block">
              <div class="code-head">
                <span class="code-lang">python</span
                ><span class="code-label"
                  >universal template + two applied examples</span
                ><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">copy</button>
              </div>
              <pre><code><span class="cm"># UNIVERSAL VARIABLE WINDOW TEMPLATE
# Use for: "longest/shortest/min/max subarray or substring with property X"
# The 3 steps never change. Only window_state and validity condition change.</span>

<span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">variable_window</span>(arr):
    left = 0
    window_state = ...       <span class="cm"># set / dict / int / Counter</span>
    result = 0               <span class="cm"># or float(&#39;inf&#39;) for minimum problems</span>

    <span class="kw">for</span> right <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(<span class="py-bi">len</span>(arr)):

        <span class="cm"># STEP 1 - EXPAND: incorporate arr[right] into window</span>
        <span class="cm"># window_state = add(window_state, arr[right])</span>

        <span class="cm"># STEP 2 - SHRINK:
        # For MAXIMUM: while window INVALID, remove arr[left], left++
        # For MINIMUM: while window VALID,   record, remove arr[left], left++</span>
        <span class="kw">while</span> is_invalid(window_state):
            <span class="cm"># window_state = remove(window_state, arr[left])</span>
            left += 1

        <span class="cm"># STEP 3 - RECORD (for maximum: after shrink loop)</span>
        result = <span class="py-bi">max</span>(result, right - left + 1)

    <span class="kw">return</span> result


<span class="cm"># APPLIED 1: Longest Substring with At Most K Distinct Characters</span>
<span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">longest_k_distinct</span>(s, k):
    freq = {}
    left = 0; result = 0
    <span class="kw">for</span> right <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(<span class="py-bi">len</span>(s)):
        freq[s[right]] = freq.get(s[right], 0) + 1       <span class="cm"># EXPAND</span>
        <span class="kw">while</span> <span class="py-bi">len</span>(freq) &gt; k:                             <span class="cm"># SHRINK</span>
            freq[s[left]] -= 1
            <span class="kw">if</span> freq[s[left]] == 0: <span class="kw">del</span> freq[s[left]]
            left += 1
        result = <span class="py-bi">max</span>(result, right - left + 1)            <span class="cm"># RECORD</span>
    <span class="kw">return</span> result


<span class="cm"># APPLIED 2: Max Consecutive Ones III (flip at most k zeros to ones)</span>
<span class="kw">def</span> <span class="fn">longest_ones</span>(nums, k):
    zero_count = 0
    left = 0; result = 0
    <span class="kw">for</span> right <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="py-bi">range</span>(<span class="py-bi">len</span>(nums)):
        <span class="kw">if</span> nums[right] == 0: zero_count += 1              <span class="cm"># EXPAND</span>
        <span class="kw">while</span> zero_count &gt; k:                             <span class="cm"># SHRINK</span>
            <span class="kw">if</span> nums[left] == 0: zero_count -= 1
            left += 1
        result = <span class="py-bi">max</span>(result, right - left + 1)            <span class="cm"># RECORD</span>
    <span class="kw">return</span> result

<span class="cm"># Both examples: Time O(n), Space O(k) or O(1)</span></code></pre>
            </div>
            <div class="callout tip">
              <div class="callout-title">
                &#9989; When to Reach for Sliding Window
              </div>
              <p>
                Signal words: <strong>contiguous subarray/substring</strong>,
                <strong>longest/shortest/min/max with condition X</strong>,
                <strong>at most k distinct</strong>,
                <strong>sum &ge; target</strong>. The condition must be
                incrementally updatable in O(1) (or O(log n) with sorted
                structure). If computing the condition requires scanning the
                entire current window, sliding window does not apply.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="callout insight">
              <div class="callout-title">
                &#128161; Two Pointers vs Sliding Window &mdash; The Decision
                Rule
              </div>
              <p>
                <strong>Use Two Pointers:</strong> sorted array, pair/triplet
                sums, palindromes, in-place partition. Pointers converge toward
                each other. <strong>Use Sliding Window:</strong> contiguous
                subarray/substring, longest/shortest/min/max qualifier,
                condition depends on window <em>content</em>. Window always
                advances left-to-right, never reverses.
                <strong>Key test:</strong> does sorting the array help? Yes
                &rarr; Two Pointers. Is the problem about a contiguous range?
                Yes &rarr; Sliding Window.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>
        <hr class="divider" />
        <section class="section" id="check">
          <div class="section-number">
            Section 0K <span class="sn-label">Knowledge Check</span>
          </div>
          <h2 class="sec-title">Questions &mdash; <em>No Peeking</em></h2>
          <p class="sec-lead">
            Answer each question before revealing. The ones you fumble are
            exactly what you revise tomorrow morning. Spend at least 60 seconds
            on each before hitting Reveal.
          </p>
          <div class="check-grid">
            <div class="check-item">
              <div class="check-q">Q01 / 08</div>
              <div class="check-text">
                Explain why two pointers on a sorted array is O(n) and not
                O(n&sup2;). State the invariant precisely.
              </div>
              <button class="check-btn" onclick="revealAnswer(this)">
                Reveal Answer
              </button>
              <div class="check-reveal">
                <strong>Invariant:</strong> when
                <code>nums[L]+nums[R] &lt; target</code>,
                <code>nums[L]</code> paired with <em>any</em> value &le;
                <code>nums[R]</code> is also too small &mdash; L is permanently
                eliminated. Advance L. Symmetrically, when sum &gt; target, R is
                eliminated. Each step eliminates exactly one element
                permanently. n elements &rarr; at most n steps &rarr; O(n).
                Neither pointer ever reverses.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="check-item">
              <div class="check-q">Q02 / 08</div>
              <div class="check-text">
                In 3Sum, name both duplicate-skip locations. What fails if you
                miss each?
              </div>
              <button class="check-btn" onclick="revealAnswer(this)">
                Reveal Answer
              </button>
              <div class="check-reveal">
                <strong>Skip #1 &mdash; outer loop:</strong>
                <code>if i &gt; 0 and nums[i] == nums[i-1]: continue</code>.
                Missing it: triplets appear multiple times when there are
                duplicate outer values. <br /><strong
                  >Skip #2 &mdash; after found triplet:</strong
                >
                advance L past all <code>nums[left]==nums[left+1]</code> and R
                past all <code>nums[right]==nums[right-1]</code>. Missing it:
                the two-pointer loop generates the same triplet repeatedly when
                duplicate values exist at L or R.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="check-item">
              <div class="check-q">Q03 / 08</div>
              <div class="check-text">
                Why does the inner <code>while</code> in variable sliding window
                NOT make it O(n&sup2;)? State the amortized argument.
              </div>
              <button class="check-btn" onclick="revealAnswer(this)">
                Reveal Answer
              </button>
              <div class="check-reveal">
                <code>left</code> only moves right &mdash; it never reverses.
                Across the entire algorithm, <code>left</code> advances at most
                <strong>n times total</strong>, regardless of how many
                individual while iterations fire per outer loop iteration. Total
                inner-loop cost across all iterations: O(n). Add O(n) outer:
                total O(n).
                <strong
                  >This exact argument applies to every shrinking-window
                  problem.</strong
                >
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="check-item">
              <div class="check-q">Q04 / 08</div>
              <div class="check-text">
                State the fixed-window slide formula. What does each term
                represent?
              </div>
              <button class="check-btn" onclick="revealAnswer(this)">
                Reveal Answer
              </button>
              <div class="check-reveal">
                <code>window_sum = window_sum + nums[i] - nums[i-k]</code>.
                <code>nums[i]</code> = new element entering the right side of
                the window. <code>nums[i-k]</code> = old element leaving the
                left side. One addition + one subtraction = O(1) per slide.
                Build first window with <code>sum(nums[:k])</code> in O(k).
                Subsequent slides: O(1). Total: O(n).
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="check-item">
              <div class="check-q">Q05 / 08</div>
              <div class="check-text">
                Minimum window vs maximum window &mdash; how does the shrink
                condition differ?
              </div>
              <button class="check-btn" onclick="revealAnswer(this)">
                Reveal Answer
              </button>
              <div class="check-reveal">
                <strong>Maximum (e.g., longest without repeat):</strong> while
                window INVALID &rarr; shrink &rarr; record after shrink loop.
                <br /><strong
                  >Minimum (e.g., shortest subarray with sum &ge;
                  target):</strong
                >
                while window VALID &rarr; record FIRST (inside loop), then
                shrink. The inversion: for minimum, you keep shrinking as long
                as the window is valid, recording each valid length before
                removing an element.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="check-item">
              <div class="check-q">Q06 / 08</div>
              <div class="check-text">
                Write the 3-step variable window template from memory.
              </div>
              <button class="check-btn" onclick="revealAnswer(this)">
                Reveal Answer
              </button>
              <div class="check-reveal">
                1. <strong>EXPAND:</strong> add <code>arr[right]</code> to
                window state every iteration. 2. <strong>SHRINK:</strong> while
                invalid (max) or valid (min), remove <code>arr[left]</code> and
                left++. 3. <strong>RECORD:</strong> for max: after shrink loop.
                For min: inside shrink loop before removing. Right moves n
                times; left moves at most n times total = O(n).
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="check-item">
              <div class="check-q">Q07 / 08</div>
              <div class="check-text">
                For LC #3, describe both the set version and dict version. What
                is the practical difference?
              </div>
              <button class="check-btn" onclick="revealAnswer(this)">
                Reveal Answer
              </button>
              <div class="check-reveal">
                <strong>Set version:</strong>
                <code>while s[right] in char_set: remove s[left], left++</code>.
                Left advances one step at a time until duplicate is gone.
                <br /><strong>Dict version:</strong>
                <code>last_seen[c] = index</code>. When duplicate found at
                right, set <code>left = last_seen[c]+1</code> directly &mdash;
                jump over multiple characters in one step. Same O(n)
                asymptotics. Dict version has fewer iterations in practice.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="check-item">
              <div class="check-q">Q08 / 08</div>
              <div class="check-text">
                What is the time complexity of 3Sum and why cannot we do better
                than O(n&sup2;)?
              </div>
              <button class="check-btn" onclick="revealAnswer(this)">
                Reveal Answer
              </button>
              <div class="check-reveal">
                O(n&sup2;). Sorting O(n log n) + O(n) per fixed element &times;
                n elements = O(n&sup2;). <br /><strong
                  >Lower bound argument:</strong
                >
                in the worst case the output itself contains O(n&sup2;) triplets
                (e.g., input is [-n,...,-1,0,1,...,n]). Any correct algorithm
                must write the output, so &Omega;(n&sup2;) in the worst case.
                Our algorithm is therefore output-sensitive optimal.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>
        <hr class="divider" />
